  abstract = {Properties that distinguish ideophones are discussed within a framework of African languages. Whether ideophones form a separate word category is examined. In most languages ideophones perform an adverbial function, are closely linked with verbs, \& are semantic rather than syntactic. Ideophones rarely function as heads of constructions, \& in some cases represent the epitome of content words in showing almost pure content \& no syntax. In terms of their phonological status, ideophones typically violate the segmental \& prosodic constraints of their matrix language \& are governed by few phonological rules. Ideophones display little morphology; repeated or prolonged ideophones generally have an iconic component in that the elongation represents extension in time or space. Ideophones tend to be very specific - they usually evoke a concrete image, appeal to the senses, \& have a narrow meaning. They rely on nonarbitrary relations between sound \& meaning. Onomatopoeia plays an important role in the composition of ideophones, especially in terms of animal cries \& engine noises. Synesthesia refers to the pairing of certain words with nonauditory human sensations \& represents another nonarbitrary association of sound with meaning. 106 References. K. Burch},
