  title = {Phonology and Sound Symbolism of {{Korean}} Ideophones},
  abstract = {Korean has a large inventory of expressive words, known as "ideophones", that describe sounds, colors, odors, tastes, shapes, textures, appearances, gestures, actions, and emotions. In Korean, the function of ideophones is immense. They play an important role in expanding vocabulary through various derivational processes and they fulfill fundamental meanings as well as express subtle connotations not otherwise available in the lexicon. In spite of this, ideophones in Korean remain one of the least understood aspects of the language.
The question of what exactly is an ideophone in Korean is not so evident, since semantically expressive words range between those that are typically ideophonic and those that are less so. This study is an attempt to reveal the systematic nature of ideophones in Korean and the way they are interwoven in the language by offering a classification of ideophones in Korean.
By identifying [ATR] and [RTR] as morphemic features based on the phonetic correlation in sound symbolism, I offer a constrained way to treat vowel harmony in ideophones. Additionally, I address the question of supposed universal characteristics of sound symbolism in the languages of the world in view of the evidence found in the Korean data. I propose that magnitude symbolism represented by [ATR] and [RTR] vowels in Korean is motivated as follows: [ATR] vowels symbolize Augmentative, reflecting the wider pharynx resulting from advancing the tongue root; [RTR] vowels which are produced with narrower pharynx by virtue of retracting the tongue symbolize Diminutive. An analysis of consonant play in ideophones is offered in which the laryngeal features [+Constricted Glottis] and [+Spread Glottis] are identified as morphemic features which are associated with intensifying degrees.

Additionally, special focus is given to the phenomenon of reduplication in ideophones. By adopting the theory of prosodic morphology, I posit a constrained way of handling the various types of reduplication that are observed in Korean ideophones.},
