  title = {Sound Symbolism Use in Affect Verbs in {{Santa Catarina Ixtahuacan}}},
  abstract = {Anthropological linguists continue to investigate sound symbolism, even though the subject is dismissed out of hand by some mainstream linguists. Prominent scholars offered insights earlier in the century. Now, a recent Berkeley volume exemplifies wider, multi-disciplinary interests. A focus of scholarship that offers investigative promise involves a type of verb, common in the word's languages, that conveys a particular sense of immediacy, emotion, and vividness. In Australian and African languages, these verbs are called ideophones, in Japanese gitaigo, and in Mayan languages affect verbs. But relevant Mayan studies have only been realized in the Greater Tzeltalan family. The reasons have to do with the readily identifiable morphosyntactic markers that characterize these verbs in those languages. However, languages are more than the sums of their grammatical markers. Cognate verbs and suffixes are found in K'iche'. These K'iche' verbs are prominent in the same domains (e.g., ethnosymptomatology) in which they are found in the Chiapas languages. The relationships between these words across languages are striking. In K'iche' they seem to be used mostly by older people in culture-specific activities, and also include some morphosyntactic features of their own such as lexical and feature metathesis, as well as certain semantic characteristics--for example, their use of "saliency devices" such as metonymy and sound symbolism. K'ichean sound symbolism can be divided into three forms: (1) phonemic (in which semantic values for the language's phonemes are identifiable); (2) onomatopoeic (in which most of the roots of the language are seen to be sound symbolic via a kuub'an kind of construction, and (3) desinence or "form" symbolism, in which the desinence contributes to a stem's semantic value. Phonemic symbolism often involves a figure/ground relationship between the initial and final consonants such that one modifies or "fine tunes" the other. The town of Santa Catarina Ixtahuac{\'a}n, the site for this study, has recently experienced traumatic cultural changes. The changes that are occurring beneath the surface are even profounder than the dramatic changes involving the relocation of the town, which occurred above it. These changes threaten the existence of traditional language forms such as affect verbs and sound symbolism.},
