f the systems of the daughter languages. Generally, a statistically significant motivated support was found: 70.2\% of the forms of the languages used were identified as motivated, 9.2\textendash{}10.4\% were non-motivated and 19.4\textendash{}20.7\% reversed-motivated. Due to the different strategies of rebuilding systems and forms, generative explanations for the motivated support should be excluded. Hence, iconicity seemed to be reintroduced after the decay, by means of language change, of a former (motivated) deictic system. Therefore, it turned out as a very likely conclusion that iconicity has been and is involved in the rebuilding of deictic material, relating to the systems as such.},
